Composed of history, memoir, and political critique, In Search of Lost Meaning shines a spotlight on the changes in Poland and the Eastern Bloc in the post-1989 years. Michnik asks what mistakes were made and what we can learn from climactic events in Poland’s past, in its literature, and the histories of Central and Eastern Europe. He calls attention to pivotal moments in which central figures like Lech Walesa and political movements like Solidarity came into being, how these movements attempted to uproot the past, and how subsequent events have ultimately challenged Poland’s enduring ethical legacy of morality and liberalism. Reflecting on the most recent efforts to grapple with Poland’s Jewish history and residual guilt, this profoundly important book throws light not only on recent events, but also on the thinking of one of their most important protagonists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSocial changezEurope, Eastern. 0aSocial changezPoland. 0aSocial ethicszPoland. 0aSocial ethics. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aactivism.  aanti semitism.  acentral europe.  acold war.  acommunism.  adissident.  aeastern bloc.  aeastern europe.  aeurope.  aeuropean union.  agenocide.  aguilt.  ahistory.  aholocaust.  ajewish history.  alech walesa.  aliberalism.  amemoir.  amodern history.  amorality.  anonfiction.  apoland.  apolish jews.  apolish literature.  apolitical action.  apolitical movements.  apolitics.  apost cold war.  arebellion.  ared scare.  arussia.  asocial justice.  asolidarity.  aussr.  awar.1 aDarnton, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGross, Irena Grudzinska, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHavel, Václav, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab